The inradius of any triangle has $rs = A$, where $r$ is the radius of the inscribed circle, $s$ is the semi-perimeter of the triangle, and $A$ is the area of the triangle. Thus,

\begin{align*} r = \frac{A}{s} = &\frac{ab/2}{(a+b+c)/2} = \frac{ab}{a+b+c} \\ d = 2r &= \frac{2ab}{a+b+c} \end{align*}If we multiply both sides by the "conjugate" of $(a+b+c)$, we get

